<HEAD>For Release Thursday, Jan. 19</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Thursday, Jan. 19, the 19th day of 1989. There are 346
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On Jan. 19, 1937, millionaire Howard Hughes set a
transcontinental air record by flying his monoplane from Los Angeles
to Newark, N.J., in 7 hours, 28 minutes and 25 seconds.
   On this date:
   In 1736, James Watt, the inventor of the steam engine, was born
in Scotland.
   In 1807, Robert E. Lee, the commander-in-chief of the Confederate
armies, was born in Stratford, Va.
   In 1809, author Edgar Allan Poe was born in Boston.
   In 1825, Ezra Daggett and his nephew, Thomas Kensett, obtained a
patent for their process of storing food in tin cans.
   In 1853, Verdi's opera ``Il Trovatore'' premiered in Rome.
   In 1861, Georgia seceded from the Union.
   In 1955, a presidential news conference was filmed for television
for the first time, with the permission of President Dwight D.
Eisenhower.
   In 1977, in one of his last official acts of office, President
Gerald R. Ford pardoned Iva Toguri D'Aquino, an American who had
made wartime broadcasts for Japan as ``Tokyo Rose.''
   In 1987, Guy Hunt became Alabama's first Republican governor
since 1874 as he was sworn into office, succeeding George C. Wallace
and marking the end of a political era.
   Ten years ago: Former Attorney General John N. Mitchell was
released on parole after serving 19 months at a federal prison at
Maxwell Air Force Base in Alabama _ the last of the convicted
Watergate defendants to be freed.
   Five years ago: The California Supreme Court rejected a petition
from quadriplegic Elizabeth Bouvia, who wanted to starve herself to
death in a public hospital, rather than live with what she called a
``useless body'' left crippled by cerebral palsy.
   One year ago: State Farm Insurance Company in California
announced it had agreed to pay $1.3 million dollars to settle a
lawsuit brought by three women who claimed they had been victims of
sexual discrimination while employed by State Farm.
   Today's Birthdays: Actress Jean Stapleton is 66. Actor Fritz
Weaver is 63. PBS newsman Robert MacNeil is 58. Movie director
Richard Lester is 57. Singer Phil Everly is 50. Actress Shelley
Fabares is 45. Singer Dolly Parton is 43. ABC newswoman Ann Compton
is 42. Actor Desi Arnaz Jr. is 36.
   Thought for Today: ``We think in generalities, but we live in
detail.'' -- Alfred North Whitehead, British philosopher (1861-1947).
</TEXT>
